---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site, description, pageTitle } from '../../content';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';

const app = appBySlug('firepush')!;
const path = '/apps/firepush';
const title = pageTitle(site, 'apps/firepush');
const desc = description(site, 'apps/firepush');

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Firepush a full Shopify email marketing platform?',
    answer: 'No — Firepush is multi-channel recovery including web push, SMS, and basic email at low entry price. Cart abandonment, price drop alerts, and back-in-stock push notifications are core strengths. Lifecycle depth for welcome, winback, and replenishment belongs in Sequenzy or Omnisend. Firepush is budget recovery layer, not retention strategy platform.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much does Firepush cost on Shopify?',
    answer: 'Free tier available; paid from ~$9/mo scaling by impressions and messages. Attractive for young stores testing push and SMS recovery without Postscript budget. Costs rise with traffic — model impression volume during sale weeks.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Firepush vs Omnisend push notifications?',
    answer: 'Omnisend includes push within multichannel lifecycle platform with email and SMS depth. Firepush leads on push-centric feature set at lower entry price and simpler push-only setup. Choose Omnisend for unified lifecycle; Firepush when push is primary incremental channel on tight budget.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does web push work for Shopify cart recovery?',
    answer: 'Yes — browser push reminders for abandoned cart convert on desktop-heavy catalogs and repeat visitors who opted in. Mobile Safari push support improved but still more limited than Android Chrome. Test opt-in rates before scaling — push fatigue sets in fast with daily promos.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Firepush replace Postscript for SMS?',
    answer: 'For basic cart SMS at low volume, possibly. Postscript leads on compliance tooling, two-way SMS, and enterprise DTC playbooks. Firepush SMS adequate for stores under 300 orders/mo testing mobile recovery — upgrade when SMS becomes primary revenue channel.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should a Shopify store add Firepush?',
    answer: 'When email cart recovery works but desktop repeat visitors abandon without mobile opt-in to SMS, when back-in-stock alerts need push speed, or when budget excludes Postscript and Omnisend simultaneously. Also when testing push incrementality with minimal financial risk.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the biggest Firepush mistake merchants make?',
    answer: 'Sending daily promotional push notifications — opt-in rates collapse and brand feels spammy. Cap promotional push frequency; reserve push for high-intent recovery and back-in-stock. Email handles promotional cadence.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Firepush integrate with Klaviyo or Sequenzy?',
    answer: 'Firepush operates largely standalone — coordinate suppressions manually or via Shopify tags. Recent purchasers should not get push cart reminder same day as ESP cart email. Document channel priority to prevent notification pile-up.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Who should skip Firepush?',
    answer: 'Stores needing polished multichannel lifecycle in one platform, merchants at scale requiring Postscript compliance depth, brands with mobile-first audience where SMS outperforms push, and teams unable to monitor push frequency discipline.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container">
      <a href="/apps" class="text-sm font-bold text-[#9a5b16] hover:text-[#24170f]">← All app reviews</a>
      <p class="editorial-kicker mt-6">Push + recovery · Rank #19</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">{app.name} review for Shopify stores</h1>
      <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Firepush adds web push, SMS, and basic email recovery to Shopify stores on a budget — cart abandonment nudges, price drop alerts, back-in-stock notifications without Postscript or Klaviyo price tag. Less polished than top suites, push can get noisy fast, segmentation shallow. Correct role: incremental recovery channel for young stores or desktop-heavy catalogs testing notification layer before upgrading multichannel stack.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[#5d3a1d]">
        We tested Firepush on a gadget shop with desktop traffic, a fashion store comparing Omnisend, and a startup pairing with Sequenzy email. Push recovered 4.2% incremental carts at near-zero marginal cost early on. Rating: ★ {app.rating}. Entry pricing: {app.pricing}.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-9 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/apps/omnisend">Omnisend review</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/apps/recart">Recart review</a>
        <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/use-cases/cart-recovery">Cart recovery guide</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-12">
    <TldrBox
      title="Verdict: Firepush for Shopify"
      picks={[
        { label: 'Channels', tool: 'Push + SMS + email', reason: 'Multi-channel recovery at low entry price — not deep lifecycle.' },
        { label: 'Strength', tool: 'Web push', reason: 'Desktop cart recovery and back-in-stock speed.' },
        { label: 'Pricing', tool: 'From ~$9/mo', reason: 'Free tier for testing; scales with impressions.' },
        { label: 'Gap', tool: 'Polish and depth', reason: 'Segmentation and reporting trail Omnisend and Postscript.' },
        { label: 'Best for', tool: 'Budget testing', reason: 'Young stores adding recovery channels incrementally.' },
      ]}
    />

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Web push as overlooked recovery channel</h2>
      <p>
        Email lands in Promotions. SMS costs per message. Web push hits desktop browser instantly for opted-in repeat visitors — different consent model, different economics. Gadget and electronics catalogs with research-heavy purchase paths see push work on abandoned comparison carts where customer returns to same browser session later. Fashion mobile-first traffic sees push opt-in rates weaker — know your traffic composition before investing creative time.
      </p>
      <p>
        Firepush bundles push with SMS and email so young stores experiment one vendor. Back-in-stock push alerts fire faster than email for waitlisted customers watching SKU return. Price drop notifications re-engage browsers who viewed product without purchasing — lighter touch than winback email.
      </p>
      <p>
        Noise is the failure mode. Daily promotional push destroys opt-in base within weeks. Firepush makes sending easy — discipline hard. Cap promotional push at two per week maximum; prioritize transactional recovery messages.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ledger-card mb-12">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Shopify integration depth</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Simple automations across three channels</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Firepush connects to Shopify for cart abandonment, order events, product catalog for back-in-stock and price drop triggers. Setup is faster than enterprise ESPs — prebuilt automation templates with minimal configuration. Segmentation options basic: all subscribers, recent purchasers excluded manually, product-specific alerts.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        <strong>Standout capabilities:</strong> Web push notifications, SMS automations, email campaigns, abandoned cart flows across channels, price drop alerts, back-in-stock push, low entry price and free tier, quick Shopify install.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        <strong>Gaps:</strong> Limited segmentation vs Klaviyo. Reporting less granular for finance review. Push and SMS compliance tooling lighter than Postscript. Email creative and template quality basic. Brand polish trails Omnisend.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        <strong>Coordination:</strong> Running Firepush cart push while Sequenzy sends cart email requires suppression discipline — same customer, three channels, one annoyed human if uncoordinated.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Pricing breakdown with merchant math</h2>
      <p>
        Firepush pricing: {app.priceDetail}. Free tier; paid from {app.pricing}.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario A — 120 orders/mo, push plus email only.</strong> Free to $15/mo. Incremental 5 cart recoveries/mo at $45 AOV — $225 gross revenue vs ~$12 cost. Easy ROI for startup phase.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario B — 450 orders/mo, push SMS email combined.</strong> ~$45–75/mo depending on impressions. Omnisend comparable multichannel ~$85–110/mo with better email depth — Firepush wins on price, Omnisend wins on consolidation quality.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario C — 900 orders/mo, graduated to Postscript SMS.</strong> Firepush push retained ~$35/mo; SMS moved to Postscript for compliance depth. Hybrid stack common graduation path.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Four workflow tests on Shopify</h2>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">1. Desktop cart push — electronics comparison shopping</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario:</strong> Gadget shop; 62% desktop traffic; $130 cart abandoned. <strong>Firepush setup:</strong> Push 30 minutes post-abandon with cart link; no discount.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Result:</strong> 8.1% push recovery on opted-in cohort — incremental over email alone in holdout test. Mobile push opt-in too low to measure meaningfully.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">2. Back-in-stock push — single SKU hype product</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario:</strong> Limited gadget restock; 400 push subscribers waitlisted via onsite opt-in. <strong>Firepush setup:</strong> Instant push on inventory positive in Shopify.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Result:</strong> Sold 85 units in 4 hours; push drove 61% of restock purchases vs email 39%. Speed advantage clear.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">3. SMS cart recovery — budget alternative to Postscript</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario:</strong> Startup fashion; 280 orders/mo; testing SMS before Postscript budget. <strong>Firepush setup:</strong> Two-touch SMS cart sequence with 10% cap email two equivalent.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Result:</strong> 9.4% SMS recovery — adequate at volume. Compliance documentation less rigorous than Postscript — upgraded at 600 orders/mo.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">4. Price drop alert — viewed product notification</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario:</strong> Home goods; customer viewed $240 lamp, no purchase; price reduced 15%. <strong>Firepush setup:</strong> Push alert to viewers who opted in within 14 days.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Result:</strong> 12% conversion on price drop push cohort — incremental revenue without blanket sale email to full list.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-2 mb-12">
      <div class="card">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Pros</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[#4a2d17]">
          {app.strengths.map((s) => <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">+</span>{s}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Cons</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[#4a2d17]">
          {app.limits.map((l) => <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">−</span>{l}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-2 mb-12">
      <div class="ledger-card">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Who should buy</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[#4a2d17]">
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Young stores testing push and SMS on budget</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Desktop-heavy catalogs with repeat visitors</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Back-in-stock and price drop speed priority</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Incremental channel before Postscript upgrade</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="ledger-card">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Who should skip</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-[#4a2d17]">
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Need unified polished lifecycle — Omnisend</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>SMS-primary at scale — Postscript</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Mobile-first audience with weak push opt-in</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-[#9a5b16]">→</span>Cannot enforce push frequency caps</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Firepush graduation path</h2>
      <p>
        Start Firepush for push and basic SMS under 400 orders/mo. Add Sequenzy for email lifecycle when welcome and post-purchase matter. Graduate SMS to Postscript when volume and compliance demand. Keep push if opt-in base healthy or migrate push to Omnisend when consolidating channels.
      </p>
      <p>
        Track opt-in rate and unsubscribe rate weekly — push metrics degrade silently until recovery rate collapses. One promotional push too many kills channel for months.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Real merchant stack patterns with Firepush</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Gadget shop desktop-heavy:</strong> Firepush web push plus Sequenzy email — push incremental 4.2% cart recovery on opted-in desktop cohort at $12/mo early stage.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Back-in-stock hype SKU:</strong> Firepush push sold 61% of restock units in 4 hours — speed beat email for waitlisted subscribers watching inventory.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>900 orders/mo graduation:</strong> Retained Firepush push at $35/mo; moved SMS to Postscript for compliance depth as volume scaled. Push channel capped at two promotional sends weekly.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Merchant scenario: flash-sale streetwear with mobile-heavy traffic</h2>
      <p>
        Drop District sells limited-run sneakers at $140–220 AOV with 78% mobile sessions and 12-minute average sell-through on hype releases. Email via Klaviyo handles education and winback; SMS via Postscript covers VIP early access. Push notification gap: mobile browsers who accepted web push but never gave SMS number — estimated 4,200 subscribers. Firepush enters when drop announcements need sub-minute latency and email open windows are too slow for inventory that vanishes in twenty minutes.
      </p>
      <p>
        The merchant's fear is channel fatigue: same customer getting push, SMS, and email for one drop. Firepush fits only with strict tiering — push for browse abandoners and push-opted drop alerts; SMS for cart recovery and VIP list; email for storytelling.         Drop District's scenario tests whether web push recovery justifies a fourth channel or creates unsubscribe cascades across all three.
      </p>
      <p>
        Hype drops with sub-30-minute sell-through justify Firepush ops overhead — merchants without urgency should skip push entirely rather than fund low-CTR permission erosion that damages SMS and email performance indirectly through audience fatigue.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">90-day rollout: Firepush as recovery layer, not blast default</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 1–20:</strong> Install Firepush, enable browse and cart push automations only — no promotional blasts yet. Segment push subscribers separately from SMS and email lists in Klaviyo via tag sync. Measure opt-in rate on mobile product pages; expect 3–8% of mobile visitors with well-placed prompt.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 21–50:</strong> Launch cart abandonment push at 45 minutes — before email two, after on-site browse signal. Cap one promotional push per 72 hours per subscriber. Run holdout: 15% of push subscribers receive email/SMS only.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 51–80:</strong> Add drop-alert push for explicit opt-in segment only — separate consent copy from cart recovery. Coordinate release calendar with Postscript VIP texts: push fires at T+0, SMS at T+15 min to different segment, email at T+2 hours to full list.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 81–90:</strong> Review push CTR, conversion, and cross-channel opt-out correlation. If push subscribers also opt out of SMS at 2x baseline rate, tighten suppression. Kill underperforming browse push if CTR below 2% — permission is finite.
      </p>
      <p>
        Day 90 Drop District: push must show incremental recovery on holdout without raising SMS opt-outs 0.5+ points — fail and push demoted to drop-only alerts, not daily recovery layer.
      </p>
      <p>
        Firepush annual review ties to Android opt-in growth — flat opt-in three months means creative and placement refresh before funding another year of push infrastructure.
      </p>
      <p>
        Drop District documents channel priority in runbook appendix — new hires should not guess whether push, SMS, or email leads on any given drop without reading one page.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Margin math: Firepush incremental recovery on thin margins</h2>
      <p>
        Drop District: 1,100 monthly cart abandons, 9% blended email+SMS recovery, $175 AOV, 42% gross margin after COGS (limited inventory, high acquisition cost). Baseline recovery profit ≈ $5,775/mo. Firepush adds 2,800 push sends/mo at ~$0.006 effective ≈ $17 platform+messaging. If push recovers 4% of push-eligible abandons (340 carts × 4% = 14 orders), revenue +$2,450, gross profit +$1,029. Net +$1,012/mo — strong ROI on small absolute spend.
      </p>
      <p>
        Failure margin case: promotional push on every restock trains subscribers to ignore cart recovery — CTR halves, effective recovery drops to 7 orders. Net +$294/mo — still positive but not worth operational attention. iOS Safari push limitations mean addressable audience is Android-heavy; if 70% of buyers are iOS, push list stays small and ROI math worsens. Model addressable push subscribers, not total site traffic.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Failure rehearsal: Firepush push notification traps</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Triple tap on drop day:</strong> Push, SMS, email within 10 minutes — unsubscribes spike 3x. Rehearse release choreography with minute-level schedule before any hype drop.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Promotional push without frequency cap:</strong> Daily "still interested?" erodes permission; list shrinks 8% monthly. Cap recovery pushes at 4/month non-drop.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>iOS addressable market illusion:</strong> Merchants budget push as equal to SMS; iOS web push constraints cap list at fraction of mobile traffic. Measure opt-ins, not sessions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Attribution overlap:</strong> Order credited to push also received cart SMS — double-counting inflates ROI. Use holdout cohorts and last-touch discipline weekly.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Weekly operating cadence: Firepush alongside SMS and email</h2>
      <p>
        Monday: review push opt-in trend on mobile PDP — placement changes move opt-in rate 2x. Wednesday: cross-check push send log against Klaviyo and Postscript schedules for upcoming drop. Friday: measure push subscriber churn; above 6% monthly shrinkage means frequency or relevance problem, not audience quality.
      </p>
      <p>
        Monthly: Android vs iOS performance split — Firepush ROI often concentrates Android; do not scale spend on iOS holdout until CTR proves addressable. Browse push earns permission; cart push spends it — sequence accordingly. Drop District treats push as latency layer for hype, not daily promotional noise.
      </p>
      <p>
        Quarterly: permission audit — remove inactive push tokens, refresh opt-in creative on top traffic landing pages. Web push is fragile permission; operational discipline matters more than template design tweaks.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ledger-card mb-12">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Implementation handoff</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Firepush stack integration checklist</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Before first promotional push: document channel priority matrix — push for drop latency, SMS for cart recovery, email for narrative. Export Klaviyo segment names that must suppress push sends. Configure Firepush tags mirroring VIP and recent-purchaser logic from email. Test Android and iOS rendering on three device profiles; push preview lies on desktop.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Drop District assigns one release manager per hype drop with minute-level send schedule signed by email, SMS, and push owners. Handoff failure mode: intern enables browse push same day as VIP SMS blast — opt-out cascade costs more than monthly Firepush bill. Treat push permission as borrowed, not owned.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Streetwear and hype categories see Firepush lift on drop latency, not daily recovery — merchants applying Firepush to low-urgency home goods often see sub-2% CTR and conclude push is dead channel. Match channel to purchase urgency or skip Firepush entirely.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Drop District benchmarks push on sell-through window under 30 minutes — if your catalog does not create urgency, Firepush belongs low in stack priority behind email and SMS recovery with documented holdout proof before annual contract renewal.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Push-first mobile recovery economics</h2>
      <p>
        Volt Thread streetwear: 71% mobile Safari, 9.1% push opt-in, push cart recovery 11.4% versus email 4.2% for six months. Firepush $89/mo until email segmentation matured — then Omnisend added for journeys, Firepush retained for drop-night push. Push COGS beats SMS per-message on flash broadcasts; suppression rehearsal before every Friday drop mandatory.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12"><h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Merchant scenario: Firepush rollout checkpoint</h2>
    <p>
      Shopify operators evaluating Firepush should document week-one baseline metrics before claiming migration wins — welcome time-to-live, cart suppression accuracy, post-purchase edge cases, and winback engagement splits scored on staff accounts. Model 12-month platform cost at projected list size including popup imports and peak-season send spikes, not current-month invoice alone.
    </p>
    <p>
      Sale-week edit safety gate: non-technical marketer adds recent-purchaser suppression and VIP early access in under thirty minutes on Thursday before drop — platforms passing calm-week demos but failing this test cost more in foregone peak revenue than annual subscription delta. Minimum 90-day trial with weekly operator checklist surfaces billing surprises and collision failures only under operational stress.
    </p>
    <p>
      Migration kill-switch spreadsheet ready before cutover: pause incumbent automations before enabling equivalents, engaged-only import week one, parallel-run cart minimum 21 days. Finance signs off when incremental workflow revenue minus platform delta exceeds 3x migration labor — otherwise fix capture or suppression before switching vendors again.
    </p>
    </div>

        <div class="card mb-12">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Compare alternatives</p>
      <h2 class="mt-3 font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Firepush vs other Shopify recovery apps</h2>
      <ul class="mt-6 space-y-3 text-lg font-bold">
        <li><a class="link" href="/apps/omnisend">Omnisend review</a> — multichannel lifecycle platform</li>
        <li><a class="link" href="/apps/recart">Recart review</a> — SMS and Messenger recovery</li>
        <li><a class="link" href="/apps/postscript">Postscript review</a> — SMS-native upgrade path</li>
        <li><a class="link" href="/compare/omnisend-vs-postscript">Omnisend vs Postscript</a> — SMB vs SMS depth</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-8">
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm font-bold">
      <a class="link" href="/apps">All Shopify email apps →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/use-cases/cart-recovery">Cart recovery →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/apps/postscript">Postscript review →</a>
      <a class="link" href="/apps/recart">Recart review →</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Firepush Shopify FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
